This paper investigates the relationship between community structure and behavioral outcomes in networks, specifically in the context of international conflict. It leverages advances in community detection in multiplex and multilayer networks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), followed by cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy), and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
